<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06329217 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06329217 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: (Esperanza Barerra and family)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  HOLIDAY; NEWSPAPER; CHARITY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Families rarely come more close-knit than 41-year-old Esperanza Barerra andher 10 children, ages 6 to 19. After moving to the Bay Area from Jalisco,Mexico, 11 years ago, Esperanza not only had to face the pressures of making afresh start in this country, but she also had to endure 19 years in a verydifficult marriage. Her husband left a year and half ago. &quot;When he first left,I locked myself in a room and I wouldn't come out,&quot; Esperanza says through aninterpreter. &quot;I couldn't take care of the kids. I would get depressed and thekids would get sick. I knew I had to snap out of it.&quot; Now, Esperanza, whoworks part time as a janitor, and all the children live in a two-bedroom housein South San Jose. After paying rent on their cramped quarters, the familysurvives on $100 a month. And when it's time to sleep, the family makes dowith four old single beds, a larger one that accommodates three people andthree broken-down sofas. A gift of four new bunk beds ($2,078.40 19A) aqueen-size bed ($433 19B), bedding for all ($638.68 19C), four dressers($1,732 19D) and a floor lamp ($129.90 19E) would make this holiday season aspecial one for the Barreras. Total: $5,011.98  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Special Section  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  19: FURNISH FAMILY WITH COMFORT AND A NEW BEGINNING  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Holiday WISH BOOK; See also related article on page 2 of this section.  </MEMO><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911124  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  241  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday, November 24, 199100329217,SJ1  </D